rative Review Board]] hearing'' \u2013 page 248 \u2013 August 10, 2005</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Hajji|Haji]] [[Nasrat Khan]]\n||\n* Hizb-I Islami Gulbuddin (HIG) was one of the major mujahedin groups in the war against the Soviets. HIG has long established ties with Usama bin Laden. [[Gulbuddin Hikmatyar]] founded HIG. Hikmatyar ran several terrorist training camps in Afghanistan and was a pioneer in sending mercenary fightters to other Islamic fighting conflicts. Hikmatyar offered to shelter [[Usama bin Laden]] after he later fled Sudan in 1996.<ref name=ArbNasratKhan>[{{DoD detainees ARB|ARB_Transcript_Set_10_21352-21661.pdf#257}} Summarized transcript (.pdf)], from [[Hajji|Haji]] [[Nasrat Khan]]'s ''[[Administrative Review Board]] hearing'' \u2013 pages 257-265</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Mohamed Jawad]]\n||\n* The Hezb-E-Islami {{Sic}} organization is a terrorist organization with long-established ties to [[Osama bin Laden|Bin Laden]].<ref name=FoiEvidenceMemoMohamedJawad>\n[http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/foi/detainees/csrt_mar05.pdf#149 Summary of Evidence (.pdf)], from [[Mohamed Jawad]]'s ''[[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]''\nOctober 19, 2004 \u2013 page 149</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Juma Din]]\n||\n* HIG is a designated terrorist group with long-established links to [[Usama Bin Laden]].<ref name=CsrtJumaDin>[{{DoD detainees ARB|Set_21_1645-1688_Revised.pdf#38}} Summarized transcripts (.pdf)], from [[Juma Din]]'s ''[[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]'' \u2013 pages 38-44</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Akhtiar Mohammad (Guantanamo detainee 1036)|Akhtiar Mohammad]]\n||\n* The HiG is listed in the [[Terrorist Organization Reference Guide]] as having long-established ties with [[Usama Bin Laden]].<ref name=CsrtAkhtiarMohammad1036>\n[{{DoD detainees ARB|Set_13_1240-1291.pdf#43}} Summarized transcripts (.pdf)], from [[Akhtiar Mohammad (Guantanamo detainee 1036)|Akhtiar Mohammad]]'s ''[[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]'' \u2013 pages 43-52</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Faizullah (Guantanamo captive 919)|Faiz Ullah]]\n||\n* The '''Hizb-I Islami Gulbuddin''' {{Sic}} (HIG) has been identified as an organization which sponsor terrorism.<ref name=CsrtSummaryOfEvidence287>[http://www.dod.mil/pub/foi/detainees/csrt_Mar05.pdf#89 Summary of Evidence memo (.pdf)] prepared for [[Faizullah (Guantanamo captive 919)|Faiz Ullah]]'s ''[[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]'' \u2013 October 15, 2004 \u2013 page 89</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Jumma Jan]]\n||\n* HIG has been designated by the United States as a terrorist organization.<ref name=\"FactorsJummaJan\"/>\n|-\n|\n* [[Faizullah (Guantanamo captive 919)|Faiz Ullah]]\n||\n* The '''Hezb-e Islami Gulbuddin''' {{Sic}} (HIG) was founded by [[Gulbuddin Hikmatyar|Hikmatyar]] {{Sic}} in 1977, as a faction of the [[Hezb-e Islami]] party, and it was one of the major [[mujahedin]] groups in the [[Soviet occupation of Afghanistan|war]] against {{Sic}} [[Soviet Union|Soviets]]. HIG has long-established ties with [[Usama bin Laden]].<ref name=ArbFaizUllah>\n[{{DoD detainees ARB|ARB_Transcript_Set_9_21017-21351.pdf#174}} Summarized transcript (.pdf)], from [[Faizullah (Guantanamo captive 919)|Faiz Ullah]]'s ''[[Administrative Review Board]] hearing'' \u2013 page 174</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Rahmatullah Sangaryar]]\n* [[Hamidullah (Guantanamo detainee 1119)|Hamidullah]]\n* [[Mohammed Mussa Yakubi]]\n||\n* [[Hizb-I Islami Gulbuddin]] (HIG) is a terrorist group.<ref name=CsrtSummaryOfEvidence258>[http://www.dod.mil/pub/foi/detainees/csrt_Mar05.pdf#60 Summary of Evidence memo (.pdf)] prepared for Rahmatullah Sangaryar's ''[[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]'' \u2013 October 19, 2004 \u2013 page 60</ref><ref name=CsrtHamidullah1119>[{{DoD detainees ARB|Set_47_3130-3248.pdf#89}} Summarized transcripts (.pdf)], from [[Hamidullah (Guantanamo detainee 1119)|Hamidullah]]'s ''[[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]'' \u2013 pages 89-101</ref><ref name=ArbMohammedMussaYakubi>[{{DoD detainees ARB|ARB_Transcript_Set_11_21662-22010.pdf#298}} Summarized transcript (.pdf)], from [[Mohammed Mussa Yakubi]]'s ''[[Administrative Review Board]] hearing'' \u2013 pages 298-314</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Mohammed Mustafa Sohail]]\n||\n* Hezb-E-Islami Gulbuddin is a known terrorist organization that has long established ties to al Qaida.<ref name=CsrtMohammedMustafaSohail>[{{DoD detainees ARB|Set_33_2302-2425_Revised.pdf#24}} Summarized transcripts (.pdf)], from [[Mohammed Mustafa Sohail]]'s ''[[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]'' \u2013 pages 24-34</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Hajji|Haji]] [[Nasrat Khan]]\n||\n* The HIG is an active terrorist organization in Afghanistan with long established ties to [[Usama Bin Laden]].<ref name=CsrtNasratKhan>[{{DoD detainees ARB|Set_2_0098-0204.pdf#17}} Summarized transcripts (.pdf)], from [[Hajji|Haji]] [[Nasrat Khan]]'s ''[[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]]'' \u2013 pages 17-25</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Abdul Razak (Guantanamo detainee 1043)|Abdul Razak]]\n||\n* In the spring of 2003, Taliban supreme leader Mullah Mohammad Omar, [[Hizb-I-Islami Gulbuddin]] {{Sic}} leader [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]], and [[Usama bin Laden]] {{Sic}} agreed to unite their forces.<ref name=ArbAbdulRazak1043>[http://www.dod.mil/pubs/foi/detainees/csrt/ARB_Transcript_Set_11_21662-22010.pdf#64 Summarized transcript (.pdf)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307071014/http://www.dod.mil/pubs/foi/detainees/csrt/ARB_Transcript_Set_11_21662-22010.pdf |date=2008-03-07 }}, from [[Abdul Razak (Guantanamo detainee 1043)|Abdul Razak]]'s ''[[Administrative Review Board]] hearing'' \u2013 December 16, 2005 \u2013 page 64</ref>\n|-\n|\n* [[Gholam Ruhani]]\n||\n* The Taliban military commander is associated with '''Hizb-I Islami Gulbuddin''' {{Sic}} (HIG). The U.S. [[Department of Homeland Security]], [[Terrorist Organization Reference Guide]], states that HIG has long established ties with Usama Bin Laden {{Sic}} and has staged attacks in attempts to force United States troop withdrawal from Afghanistan.<ref name=FactorsGholamRuhani>[{{DoD detainees ARB|ARB_Factors_Set_2_1046-1160.pdf#54}} Factors for and against the continued detention (.pdf)] of [[Gholam Ruhani]] ''[[Administrative Review Board]]'', May 2, 2005 \u2013 page 54</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=tolonews2018-06-14>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/government-frees-180-hizb-e-islami-prisoners\n| title       = Government Frees 180 Hizb-e-Islami Prisoners\n| work        = [[Tolo News]]\n| author      = Gulabuddin Ghubar\n| date        = 2018-06-14\n| archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20180614234816/https://www.tolonews.com/afghanistan/government-frees-180-hizb-e-islami-prisoners\n| archivedate = 2018-06-14\n| accessdate  = 2019-04-12\n| url-status     = live \n| quote       = \u201cHizb-e-Islami leadership expects that you (released inmates) become patriotic citizens for this country,\u201d said Ghairat Baheer, head of Hizb-e-Islami-Government Peace Accord Commission.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Soviet-Afghan War}}\n{{War on Terror}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hezb-E-Islami Gulbuddin}}\n[[Category:Anti-Soviet factions in the Soviet\u2013Afghan War]]\n[[Category:Islamic political parties in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist in Asia]]\n[[Category:Peshawar Seven]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1977]]\n[[Category:Politics of Nangarhar Province]]\n[[Category:Sunni Islamist groups]]\n[[Category:Defunct organizations designated as terrorist]]\n[[Category:Organizations designated as terrorist by Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Afghan political party}}\n{{Infobox War Faction\n|name = Hezb-e Islami\n|native_name = \u062d\u0632\u0628 \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc \u06af\u0644\u0628\u062f\u06cc\u0646\n|native_name_lang = fa\n|war = the [[War in Afghanistan (1978\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]\n|image = [[File:Hezbi Islami.svg]]\n|caption =\n|leaders = [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]]\n|clans = [[Muslims]]\n|ideology = [[Islam]]ism<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAnlN82F6F0C&pg=PA141 |title=9/11 and the Wars in Afghanistan and Iraq|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n|active = 1975\u20132016 (as a militia)<br> 1975\u2013''present'' (as a political party)\n|headquarters =\n|area = [[Afghanistan]] \n|strength = 1,500\u20132,000+<ref>{{cite web|title=Afghanistan after the Western Drawdown|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DOk1CgAAQBAJ&pg=PA214 |website=Google books |date=January 16, 2015|accessdate=13 August 2015}}</ref>\n|previous = [[Muslim Youth]]\n|allies  =   {{flag|North Korea}} <small>(Allegedly)</small><ref>https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/26/afghanistan-war-logs-osama-bin-laden?intcmp=239</ref><br>{{flag|Pakistan}} <small>(Until 1994)</small><br>{{flag|Saudi Arabia}}<br>{{flag+link|Ba'athist|Iraq|variant= 1991}} <small>(1975\u20132003)</small><ref>https://kyleorton1991.wordpress.com/2015/06/29/saddam-and-the-taliban/</ref><br>{{flag|Azerbaijan}}<br>{{flagdeco|Chechen Republic of Ichkeria|size=23px}} [[Chechen Republic of Ichkeria|Chechnya]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of Taliban.svg}} [[Taliban]]<br>{{flag|al-Qaeda}}<br>{{flagdeco|ISIL}} [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant \u2013 Khorasan Province|Islamic State-Khorasan Province]] <small>(Allegedly)</small><ref>https://www.ibtimes.com/gulbuddin-hekmatyars-hezb-e-islami-announces-support-isis-afghanistan-combat-taliban-1996462</ref><ref>https://www.rferl.org/a/islamic-state-afghanistan-hekmatyar/27114317.html</ref><ref>http://www.arabnews.com/node/1219966/world</ref><ref>http://www.catchnews.com/world-news/isis-sympathiser-gulbuddin-hekmatyar-announces-participation-in-afghan-peace-talks-1457871686.html</ref>\n|opponents = {{flag|United States}} <small>(2001\u20132016)</small><br>{{flag|Afghanistan}} <small>(1975\u20132016)</small><br>{{flag|Soviet Union}} <small>(1975\u201389)</small><br>{{flag|Armenia}} <small>(1993)</small>\n|battles = [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]]<br> [[Afghan Civil War (1992\u201396)]]\n*[[Afshar Operation]]\n[[Afghan Civil War (1996\u20132001)]] <br> [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n|website =\n|identification_symbol_label = Flag\n|identification_symbol = [[File:Flag of Hezbi Islami Gulbuddin.svg|150px]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin''' ({{lang-fa|\u062d\u0632\u0628 \u0627\u0633\u0644\u0627\u0645\u06cc \u06af\u0644\u0628\u062f\u06cc\u0646}}; [[Abbreviation|abbreviated]] '''HIG'''), also referred to as '''[[Hezbi Islami|Hezb-e-Islami]]'''<ref name=\"Schism\"/> or '''Hezb-i-Islami''' Afghanistan (HIA),<ref name=\"Jamestown\" /> is an [[Afghanistan|Afghan]] political party and former militia, founded and led by [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]].\n\nSince 1979, when [[Mulavi Younas Khalis]] made a split with Hekmatyar and established his own group, the remaining part of Hezb-e Islami, still headed by Hekmatyar, was known as 'Hezb-e Islami Gulbuddin' or HIG.\n\nDuring the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] (1979\u20131989), Hezb-e Islami Gulbuddin was well-financed by anti-Soviet forces through the Pakistani [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI). In the mid-1990s, the HIG was \"sidelined from Afghan politics\" by the rise of the [[Taliban]].\n\nIn the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|post-2001 war]] in Afghanistan, HIG \"reemerged as an aggressive militant group, claiming responsibility for many bloody attacks against Coalition forces and the administration of President [[Hamid Karzai]]\".<ref name=\"Jamestown\"/>  Its fighting strength was \"sometimes estimated to number in the thousands\".<ref name=\"crowley\"/> The group signed a peace deal with the [[Ashraf Ghani|Ghani administration]] in 2016.\n\n==History==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[image:Hikmatyar 2.jpeg|thumb|[[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]]]] -->\n\n===Background: split-up Hezb-e-Islami===\nThe original [[Hezb-e-Islami]] was founded in 1975 by [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]].\n\nIn 1979, [[Mulavi Younas Khalis]] made a split with Hekmatyar and established his own group, which became known as the [[Khalis faction]], with its power base in [[Nangarhar]]. The remaining part of Hezb-e Islami, still headed by Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, was since then also known as 'Hezb-e Islami Gulbuddin' or HIG.\n\n===War against Soviet invasion===\nDuring the [[Soviet\u2013Afghan War]] (1979\u20131989), Hezb-e Islami Gulbuddin was well-financed by anti-Soviet forces, through the Pakistani [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI). Since 1981 or 1985, Hezb-e Islami Gulbuddin formed a part of the [[Peshawar Seven]] alliance of Sunni Mujaheddin forces fighting the Soviet invasion.\n\nHekmatyar and his party operated near the [[Pakistan]]i border against Soviet Communists. Areas such as [[Kunar Province|Kunar]], [[Laghman Province|Laghman]], [[Jalalabad]], and [[Paktia]] were Hezb-e Islami's strongholds. The party is highly centralized under Hekmatyar's command and until 1994 had close relations with Pakistan.<ref name=\"bergen\"/>\n\nDespite its ample funding, it has been described as having\n{{cquote|the dubious distinction of never winning a significant battle during the war, training a variety of militant Islamists from around the world, killing significant numbers of mujahideen from other parties, and taking a virulently anti-Western line. In addition to hundreds of millions of dollars of American aid, Hekmatyar also received the lion's share of aid from the Saudis.<ref name=\"bergen\">Bergen, Peter L., ''Holy War, Inc.: Inside the Secret World of Osama bin Laden'', New York : Free Press, c2001., p. 69</ref>}}\n\n=== Civil war (1992\u20132001) ===\n{{See also|Afghan Civil War (1992\u201396)|Afghan Civil War (1996\u20132001)}}\nIn April 1992, [[Hezbi Islami]] (HIG) was involved in the outbreak of [[Afghan Civil War (1992\u201396)|civil war in Afghanistan]].\n\nThe bombardment of the capital [[Kabul]] by Hezb-i-Islami Afghanistan (HIA) in 1994 is reported to have \"resulted in the deaths of more than 25,000 civilians.\"<ref name=\"Jamestown\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.jamestown.org/news_details.php?news_id=325|date=June 29, 2008|title=Gulbuddin Hekmatyar\u2019s Return to the Afghan Insurgency|author=Muhammad Tahir\n|publisher=[[Jamestown Foundation]]|accessdate=2008-07-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602104444/http://www.jamestown.org/news_details.php?news_id=325|archivedate=2008-06-02}}</ref> Frustrated by that continued destructive warlord feuding in Afghanistan, the [[Pakistan]]i [[Inter-Services Intelligence]] (ISI) abandoned HIG for the [[Taliban]] in 1994.{{Citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nAfter HIG was expelled from Kabul by the Taliban in September 1996, many of its local commanders joined the Taliban, \"both out of ideological sympathy and for reason of tribal solidarity.\"<ref name=\"Islamism, Olivier Roy 2007 p.133\">''The Columbia World Dictionary of Islamism'', Olivier Roy, Antoine Sfeir, editors, (2007), p.133</ref> In Pakistan [[Hezb-e-Islami]] training camps \"were taken over by the Taliban and handed over\" to [[Jamiat Ulema-e-Islam]] (JUI) groups such as the [[Sipah-e-Sahaba]] Pakistan (SSP).<ref>Rashid, ''Taliban'', (2000), p.92</ref>\n\n===After 2001===\n{{See also|Hezbi Islami#History since 2001}}\n''The Columbia World Dictionary of Islamism'' reports that, having lost Saudi support when it supported [[Saddam Hussein]] and [[Pakistan]]i support after 1994, \"the remainder of Hizb-i Islami merged into [[al-Qaeda]] and the Taliban.\"<ref name=\"Islamism, Olivier Roy 2007 p.133\"/> The [[Jamestown Foundation]] describes it having been \"sidelined from Afghan politics\" for a decade or so after the Taliban takeover of Kabul.<ref name=\"Jamestown\"/> Hekmatyar opposed the 2001 American intervention in Afghanistan, and since then has aligned his group (Hezb-e-Islami) with remnants of the Taliban and al-Qaeda against the current Afghan government.<ref name=\"Schism\">[http://www.jamestown.org/programs/gta/single/?tx_ttnews%5Btt_news%5D=26615&tx_ttnews%5BbackPid%5D=179&no_cache=1 Trojan Horse or Genuine Schism? The Hezb-e-islami Split], David C. Isby, June 2, 2004</ref>\n\nRadio Free Europe reports that \"in 2006, Hekmatyar appeared in a video aired on the Arabic language Al-Jazeera television station and declared he wanted his forces to fight alongside Al-Qaeda.\"<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2007/07/6B452D3C-A2E0-459E-9CE9-939411D50A04.html Afghanistan: Skeptics Urge Caution Over Purported Hekmatyar Cease-Fire] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070814233656/http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2007/07/6b452d3c-a2e0-459e-9ce9-939411d50a04.html |date=2007-08-14}} July 19, 2007</ref> According to ''[[Le Monde]]'' newspaper, as of 2007, the group was active around [[Mazari Sharif]] and [[Jalalabad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lemonde.fr/web/infog/0,47-0@2-3216,54-905049@51-907647,0.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070517072931/http://www.lemonde.fr/web/infog/0,47-0@2-3216,54-905049@51-907647,0.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=17 May 2007|title=Les zones d'influence talibanes en Afghanistan|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> HIG took credit for a 2008 attack on a military parade that nearly killed Karzai, an August 2008 ambush near Kabul that left ten French soldiers dead, and an October 3, 2009 attack by 150 insurgents that overwhelmed a remote outpost in [[Nuristan]] Province, killing eight American soldiers and wounding 24.<ref name=\"crowley\" />\n\nThere have also been reports of clashes between members of the HIG and Taliban, and defection of HIG members to the Afghan government. Ten members of the group's \"senior leadership\" met in May 2004 with President Hamid Karzai and \"publicly announced their rejection of Hezb-e-Islami\u2019s alliance with al-Qaeda and the Taliban.\"<ref name=\"Schism\" /> Prior to Afghanistan's 2004 elections, 150 members of the Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin party were said to have defected to [[Hamid Karzai]]'s administration.<ref name=Iwpr040914>{{Cite web|url=http://iwpr.net/?p=arr&s=f&o=153243&apc_state=heniarr2004|title=Commanders Line Up Behind Karzai|date=September 14, 2004|accessdate=January 15, 2007|publisher=[[Institute for War & Peace Reporting]]}}</ref> Jamestown Foundation reported in 2004 that, according to Deputy Speaker of Parliament Sardar Rahmanoglu, HIA members \"occupy around 30 to 40 percent of government offices, from cabinet ministers to provisional and other government posts.\"<ref name=\"Jamestown\" /> According to journalist Michael Crowley, as of 2010, HIG\u2019s political arm holds 19 of 246 seats in the Afghan parliament and \"claims not to take cues from Hekmatyar, though few believe it.\"<ref name=\"crowley\">[http://www.tnr.com/print/article/politics/our-man-kabul Our Man in Kabul?], Michael Crowley, ''The New Republic'', March 9, 2010</ref>\n\nIn early March 2010, elements of the Taliban and the HIG were reportedly fighting in [[Baghlan]] province.\n<blockquote>Scores of Hizb-e-Islami militants, including 11 commanders and 68 fighters, defected on Sunday [7 March 2010] and joined the Afghan government as a clash between the group and the Taliban left 79 people dead, police said.<ref>[http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2010%5C03%5C08%5Cstory_8-3-2010_pg1_3 \"Hizb-e-Islami militants fight Taliban, defect to Afghan govt\"], ''Daily Times'', 8 March 2010.</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Peace negotiations 2010\u20132016===\nOn the celebration of ''[[Nowruz]]'', New Year's Day, of 1389 (March 21, 2010, Western calendar) [[Harun Zarghun]], chief spokesman for Hizb-i-Islami, said that a five-member delegation was in Kabul to meet with government officials and that there were also plans to meet with Taliban leaders somewhere in Afghanistan. [[Khalid Farooqi]], a member of the parliament from [[Paktika]] province, confirmed that two delegations from Hizb-i-Islami had shown up. Zarghun, the group's spokesman in Pakistan, said that the delegation had a 15-point plan that called for the retreat of foreign forces in July 2010<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2010/03/hekmatyars_peace_pla.php|title=Hekmatyar's 'peace plan' calls for NATO withdrawal by 2011|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> \u2013 a full year ahead of President Barack Obama's intended withdrawal. The plan also called for the replacement of the current Afghan parliament in December 2010 by an interim government, or [[shura]], which then would hold local and national elections within a year. Zarghun said that a new Afghan constitution would be written, merging the current version with ones used earlier.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/21/AR2010032100252.html \"Militant group in Kabul with draft peace deal\"]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/21/AR2010032102933.html|title=13 die in Afghanistan amid calls for peace talks with insurgents|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2010-03-21-kabul-peace_N.htm|title=Militant group in Kabul with draft peace deal |work=USA Today|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe same day, Afghanistan's vice-president [[Mohammed Fahim|Mohammad Qasim Fahim]] reached out to militants at the Nowruz New Year celebrations in [[Mazar-i-Sharif]] in Northern Afghanistan. He declared that, with their input, a coming national conference would lay the foundations for peace. He called on resistance forces to participate in a [[jirga]], or assembly, planned for late April or early May.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/88232 |title=\"Afghanistan opens door to militants\" |access-date=2010-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120504162927/http://www.morningstaronline.co.uk/index.php/news/content/view/full/88232 |archive-date=2012-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn late January 2012, America's special envoy to the region [[Marc Grossman]] talked peace and reconciliation with [[Hamid Karzai]] in [[Kabul]], though the Afghan president made it clear that Afghans should be in the driver's seat;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/01/21/world/asia/afghanistan-grossman-talks/index.html?hpt=hp_t2|title=U.S. envoy Grossman in Afghanistan to discuss peace, Taliban |publisher=[[CNN]]|date=January 21, 2012|accessdate=January 21, 2012}}</ref> hours before the meeting, Karzai said he personally held peace talks recently with the insurgent faction [[Hizb-i-Islami]], appearing to assert his own role in a U.S.-led bid for negotiations to end the country's decade-long war.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5h6oEJHuroNlnouqUMg3DmMUJhxyA?docId=33da5aca3942409a972306720c5fc39c|title=Karzai says he's met with Afghan insurgent faction|last=Johnson|first=Kay|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 21, 2012|accessdate=January 21, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Afghan media outlets reported that Hekmatyar had called on followers of Hezb-e Islami to support the militant group [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) in the fight against the Taliban.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/islamic-state-afghanistan-hekmatyar/27114317.html|title=Afghanistan's Hekmatyar Announces Support For IS In Fight Against Taliban|publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|date=7 July 2015|first=Joanna|last=Paraszczuk}}</ref> Reuters quoted a spokesman for Hizb-i-Islami as denying this, and calling the earlier reports a fake.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/13/us-afghanistan-militants-idUSKCN0PN1SH20150713|title=Hekmatyar's Afghan militants deny joining Islamic State|publisher=Reuters|date=13 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2010 Badakhshan massacre===\nIn August 2010, Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin was possibly responsible for the [[2010 Badakhshan massacre]].<ref>[http://tolonews.com/en/afghanistan/235-hezb-e-islami-killed-2-afghans-and-8-foreigners \"Hezb-e-Islami killed 2 Afghans and 8 foreigners\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717070506/http://tolonews.com/en/afghanistan/235-hezb-e-islami-killed-2-afghans-and-8-foreigners |date=2011-07-17 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.pajhwok.com/viewstory.asp?lng=eng&id=99833 \"HIA claims killing medics\"]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english2010/world/2010-08/07/c_13434356.htm|title=2 militants groups claim responsibility for killing 8 foreigners in NE Afghanistan|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2010/08/hizbiislam_taliban_b.php|title=Hizb-i-Islami, Taliban both claim killing 10 medical workers in northern Afghanistan|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged ties to North Korea===\nAccording to a document dump in the summer of 2010, a Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin member, along with an agent of [[Osama Bin Laden]], allegedly took a trip on November 19, 2005 to [[North Korea]] via [[Iran]]. Here is the exact text of the intelligence report:\n\n{{Quote|THREAT TO AIRCRAFT IN [[Helmand Province|HELMEND PROVINCE]]\nOrganization(s) Involved: HEZB E ISLAMI GULBUDDIN\nTEXT: On 19 November 2005, Hezb-Islami party leader, [[Gulbuddin Hekmatyar]] and Dr. Amin ((nln)), [[Usama Bin Laden]]\u2019s financial advisor, both flew to North Korea departing from an Iran. They returned to Helmand //geocoord: 3100n/06400e//, Afghanistan on approximately 3 December 2005. While in North Korea, the two confirmed a deal with the North Korean government for remote controlled rockets for use against [[United States|American]] and coalition aircraft. The deal was closed for an undetermined amount of money. The shipment of said weapons is expected shortly after the new year. nfi. Upon return from North Korea Dr. Amin stayed in Helmand, and Hekmartyr went to Konar, Nuristan province<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org|title=WikiLeaks|publisher=|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>}}\n\nAlthough a rocket attack reported to have happened in 2007, killing all on board and destroying the vehicle, fit the characteristics of the mentioned North Korean rocket, the report remains unverified. No such Dr. Amin has surfaced of late.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jul/26/afghanistan-war-logs-osama-bin-laden?intcmp=239 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Simon | last=Tisdall | title=Afghanistan war logs reveal hand of Osama bin Laden | date=July 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2016 peace deal===\nOn 22 September 2016, the government of Afghanistan signed a draft peace deal with Hezb-i-Islami. According to the draft agreement, Hezb-i-Islami agreed to cease hostilities, cut ties to extremist groups and respect the Afghan Constitution, in exchange for government recognition of the group and support for the removal of [[United Nations]] and American sanctions against Hekmatyar, who was also promised an honorary post in the government.<ref>{{cite\nweb|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/23/world/asia/afghanistan-peace-deal-hezb-i-islami.html|title=Afghanistan Signs Draft Peace Deal With Faction Led by Gulbuddin Hekmatyar|date=23 September 2016|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-afghanistan-agreement-20160922-snap-story.html |title=Afghanistan takes a step toward peace with notorious ex-warlord|publisher=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nThe agreement was formalised on 29 September with both Afghan President Ashraf Ghani and Hekmatyar who appeared via a video link into the presidential palace, signing the agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/09/afghanistan-ghani-hekmatyar-sign-peace-deal-160929092524754.html |title=Afghanistan: Ghani, Hekmatyar sign peace deal|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=29 September 2016}}</ref> The Afghan government formally requested UN in December 2016 for removal of sanctions against the group's leaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aninews.in/newsdetail-NA/MjkxMDgx/afghanistan-formally-requests-un-to-remove-sanctions-against-hezb-e-islami-leaders.html|title=Afghanistan formally requests UN to remove sanctions against Hezb-e-Islami leaders|publisher=ANI News|date=12 December 2016|access-date=2016-12-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161214145011/http://www.aninews.in/newsdetail-NA/MjkxMDgx/afghanistan-formally-requests-un-to-remove-sanctions-against-hezb-e-islami-leaders.html|archive-date=2016-12-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> The sanctions against Hekmatyar were lifted by the UN on 3 February 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/lifts-sanctions-gulbuddin-hekmatyar-170204125508334.html|title=UN lifts sanctions against Gulbuddin Hekmatyar|publisher=Al-Jazeera|date=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 14, 2018, 180 individuals tied to Hezbi Islami were released from prison.<ref name=tolonews2018-06-14/>  Peace negotiator [[Ghairat Baheer]] addressed the men, on their release, telling them the party expected them to be peaceful, law-abiding citizens.  ''[[Tolo News]]'' reported that this was the fourth release of individuals tied to Hezbi Islami, and it brought the total number of released men to 500.\n\n==Accused combatant prisoners at Guantanamo==\nDozens of inmates at the United States prison at Guantanamo Bay faced allegations that they had been associated with the Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin.\n\nOriginally the [[George W. Bush|Bush]] [[United States President|Presidency]] asserted it was not obliged to let any captives apprehended in Afghanistan know why they were being held, or to provide a venue where they could challenge the allegations against them. However, the [[United States Supreme Court]]'s ruling in [[Rasul v. Bush]] required the institution of a review. The Supreme Court recommended the reviews be modeled after the [[Army Regulation 190-8 Tribunal]]s that were ordinarily used to determine whether captives were innocent civilians who should be released, [[lawful combatant]]s entitled to [[Prisoner of War]] status, or [[war criminal]]s who could be tried, and who weren't protected by all the provisions of the [[Geneva Conventions]].\n\nThe [[United States Department of Defense|Department of Defense]] set up the [[Office for the Administrative Review of Detained Enemy Combatants]] (OARDEC). OARDEC administered an initial [[Combatant Status Review Tribunal]] for the 558 [[Guantanamo captive]]s who were still in the detention camp as of August 2004. Unlike the AR 190-8 Tribunals, the Combatant Status Review Tribunals were not authorized to determine whether captives were entitled to POW status, only whether they were \"[[enemy combatant]]s. OARDEC also administered annual [[Administrative Review Board]] hearings. The Boards were only authorized to make a recommendation as to whether captives might represent an ongoing threat, or might continue to hold intelligence value, and therefore should continue to be held in US custody.\n\nClose to 10,000 pages of documents from the Combatant Status Review Tribunals and Administrative Review Board hearings were released after contested [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] requests.\n\nDozens of captives faced allegations that they had been associated with the Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin. Some of the documents just alleged that a captive was associated with Hezb-e-Islami, without explaining why this implied they were an \"enemy combatant\". Other documents did provide brief explanations as how an association with Hezb-e-Islami implied a captive was an \"enemy combatant\". Neither Hezb-e-Islami nor Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin are on the [[U.S. State Department list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations]] and they never have been;<ref>[https://2001-2009.state.gov/s/ct/rls/rpt/fto/2001/5258.htm \"2001 Report on Foreign Terrorist Organizations\"], [https://2001-2009.state.gov/s/ct/rls/fs/2002/12535.htm \"Fact Sheet: Foreign Terrorist Organizations List\" October 23, 2002]  , [https://2001-2009.state.gov/s/ct/rls/fs/2003/17065.htm \"Fact Sheet: Foreign Terrorist Organizations List\" January 30, 2003], [https://2001-2009.state.gov/s/ct/rls/fs/2004/40945.htm \"Fact Sheet: Foreign Terrorist Organization Designations Table\" December 30, 2004], [https://2001-2009.state.gov/s/ct/rls/fs/37191.htm \"Fact Sheet:Foreign Terrorist Organizations (FTOs)\" October 11, 2005] , [https://2001-2009.state.gov/s/ct/rls/crt/2005/65275.htm \"Country Reports on Terrorism: Chapter 8 -- Foreign Terrorist Organizations\" April 28, 2006]</ref> but Gulbuddin is on the additional list called \"Groups of Concern.\"<ref>[http://www.america.gov/st/washfile-english/2007/April/20070425112939idybeekcm0.9128382.html \"U.S. Designates Foreign Terrorist Organizations: List includes 42 groups, 43 others deemed \"of concern\"\" April 30, 2007]</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|\n* [[Abdullah Mujahid]]\n* [[Hajji|Haji]] [[Hamidullah (Guantanamo detainee 1119)|Hamidullah]]\n* [[Alif Mohammed]]\n* [[Adel Hassan Hamad]]\n||\n* ''\"Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin is a faction of the [[Hezb-e-Islami]] party, and it was one of the major [[mudjahedin]] groups in the [[Soviet invasion of Afghanistan|war against the Soviets]]. Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin has long-established ties with [[Osama bin Laden|Bin Ladin]].<ref name=ArbAbdullahMujahid>{{dead link|date= February 2018}}  [{{DoD detainees ARB|ARB_Transcript_Set_11_21662-22010.pdf#206}} Summarized transcript (.pdf)], from [[Abdullah Mujahid]]'s ''[[Administrative Review Board]] hearing'' \u2013 page 206\n</ref>\"<ref name=ArbHamidullah>{{dead link|date= February 2018}} [{{DoD detainees ARB|ARB_Transcript_Set_11_21662-22010.pdf#242}} Summarized transcript (.pdf)], from [[Hajji|Haji]] [[Hamidullah (Guantanamo detainee 1119)|Hamidullah]]'s ''[[Administrative Review Board]] hearing'' \u2013 page 242\n</ref><ref name=ArbAlifMohammed>\n[{{DoD detainees ARB|ARB_Transcript_Set_10_21352-21661.pdf#113}} Summarized transcript (.pdf)], from [[Alif Mohammed]]'s ''[[Administrative Review Board]] 